                     <a href="http://www.usarray.org/field_stories"><span style="font-size:10pt;"><font style="background-color: rgb(205, 222, 159);"><span style="line-height: 13px;"><b><u><span style="color:#4B0082;">USArray&nbsp;Stories from the Field</span></u></b></span></font></span></a>
                     <br style="background-color: rgb(205, 222, 159);"> 
                     <span style="font-size: 10px; background-color: rgb(205, 222, 159);">Essays about the experiences of USArray field crews, student siters, and others are now available on the <a href="http://www.usarray.org/field_stories">USArray website.</a></span>
                    </div> 
                   </div> 
                  </div> 
                 </div> 
                 <div style="margin: 0px 0px 10px; font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;"> 
                  <div style="font-size: 10px; margin: 0px 0px 10px;"> 
                   <div style="margin: 0px 0px 10px;">
                    <br> 
                    <a href="http://www.iris.edu/dms/products/sourcetimefunction"><span style="color:#4B0082;"><strong><span style="font-size:10pt;line-height: 13px;">Source-Time Function Data Product Now Available</span></strong></span></a>
                    <br> Point-source synthetic seismograms are used along with vertical component recordings of short-arc Rayleigh waves to calculate source-time functions at GSN and other stations automatically in near-real time.
